{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633169"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:49:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:49:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17467"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17467"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.3,0,0.55,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5435"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn infectious disease epidemiology, different time periods are important for understanding disease transmission and implementing control measures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the latent period of an infectious disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Time between exposure and antibody development","Time between becoming infectious and symptom onset","Time between exposure and becoming infectious to others","Time between exposure and symptom onset","Time between symptom onset and recovery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etime between exposure and becoming infectious to others\u003C/strong\u003E correctly defines the latent period. This is a crucial concept in infectious disease epidemiology as it helps determine when an individual can transmit the disease to others.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETime between exposure and antibody development\u003C/strong\u003E describes the period until seroconversion, which is a separate immunological process.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETime between becoming infectious and symptom onset\u003C/strong\u003E represents the relationship between infectiousness and symptoms, which may vary between diseases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETime between exposure and symptom onset\u003C/strong\u003E defines the incubation period, which is a distinct epidemiological concept.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETime between symptom onset and recovery\u003C/strong\u003E describes the clinical course of illness rather than the transmission dynamics.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the latent period is essential for disease control as it helps determine when isolation measures should be implemented and how long they should last. The latent period varies significantly between different infectious diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The latent period is the time between exposure to an infectious agent and becoming infectious to others.","The latent period differs from the incubation period, which is the time between exposure and symptom onset.","Understanding latent periods is crucial for implementing effective disease control measures."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ryu S, Chun JY, Lee S, et al. Epidemiology and Transmission Dynamics of Infectious Diseases and Control Measures. Viruses. 2022;14(11):2510. Published 2022 Nov 12. doi:10.3390/v14112510"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17467"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56281"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:14:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:15:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10157"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5